About the problem: Apply the definition of negative and rational exponents to rewrite a given algebraic expression.

(BA-Basics #107 BA6104)


*************************************************************-->


<problem>

<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="c" from="3" to="6"/>
  <math name="a">1/$c</math>
  <math name="b">-1/$c</math>
  <m name="expr">\sqrt[$c]{x} + \frac{1}{\sqrt[$c]{x}}</m>
  <math name="sol" simplify="numberspreserveorder">x^($a) + x^($b)</math>
</setup>


<!--testing-->
<!-- <p>a = $a</p>
<p>b = $b</p>
<p>c = $c</p>
<p>expr = $expr</p>
<p>sol = $sol</p> -->
<!--testing-->

<p>Rationalize and simplify <m>\displaystyle{f(x) = $expr}</m>. Rewrite the function in the form <m>\displaystyle{f(x) = x^a + x^b}</m>, and enter <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> below.</p>

<p><m>a = </m> <mathInput name="userA"/></p>
<p><m>b = </m> <mathInput name="userB"/></p>

<p>
    <answer name="ans1" matchPartial>
      <award name="correct">
        <when>$userA = $a and $userB = $b</when>
      </award>
    </answer></p>

